#!/bin/bash

# archy:summary=Print a security notice before installing AUR packages

cat <<'EOF'

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Installing packages from the AUR (Arch User Repository)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  The AUR is user-submitted and is NOT signed or vetted like the official
  Arch repos. It has been the vector for real malware (CHAOS RAT, Jul 2025;
  Spark RAT, Aug 2025; the "Atomic Arch" mass-hijack of 1,500+ ORPHANED
  packages, Jun 2026).

  To stay safe, this installer:
    • routes everything available in the signed repos through pacman, not AUR
    • installs the AUR packages below with PKGBUILD review ENABLED, so you can
      inspect each PKGBUILD/.install and source diff before anything is built
    • only ships actively-maintained packages that pull from their genuine,
      official upstream (none were in the Atomic Arch blast radius)

  When yay shows the diff/edit menus: actually look. Reject anything with an
  unexpected source URL or a build/install step that runs curl|sh, npm/pip/bun,
  or base64-decoded blobs. (Set ARCHY_AUR_TRUST=1 to skip review on trusted,
  automated runs.)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

EOF
sleep 2
